I got burned a while back using `?:` indiscriminately, resulting in reduced performance.

In essence, you cannot trust the `?:` operator to do the ""right""/intended thing, as it's likely to try to convert B and C to have the same type.  The number of rules applied to evaluating `A ? B : C` is ridiculous.  It's only useful for simple expressions that don't involve varying types (eg. int). Using an `if/else` block is preferred otherwise.

